values: so i have decided to start an actual blog where i write about (possibly) interesting things.  it won't be like the diary-ish approach i have used on here, rambling on about things in my life and venting.  that will probably become my major way of communicating via web, so save my new link: http://c1ndyl0u825.blogspot.com.  i may import some of my entries there into facebook or myspace too.
woohoo!  i'm leaving today to go on a cruise tomorrow for jenny's wedding!  and then as soon as i get back from that i am going up to camp for a week, yay!

You scored 52% Organization, 70% abstract, and 54% extroverted!
This test measured 3 variables.

First, this test measured how organized you are. Some muppets like Cookie Monster make big messes, while others like Bert are quite anal about things being clean.

Second, this test measured if you prefer a concrete or an abstract viewpoint. For the purposes of this test, concrete people are considered to gravitate more to mathematical and logical approaches, whereas abstract people are more the dreamers and artistic type.

Third, this test measured if you are more of an introvert or an extrovert. By definition, an introvert concentrates more on herself and an extrovert focuses more on others. In this test an introvert was somebody that either tends to spend more time alone or thinks more about herself.

You are mostly organized, more abstract, and both introverted and extroverted.

Most people either love or hate Elmo. I hope you love Elmo, because that's who you are.

You are both somewhat organized. You have a good idea where you put things and you probably keep your place reasonably clean. You aren't totally obsessed with neatness though. Elmo has the same basic approach. His place is pretty tidy, but he doesn't spend all of his time cleaning it up.

You both are abstract thinkers. You definitely are not afraid to take chances in life. You only live once. You may notice others around you playing it safe, but you are more concerned with not compromising your desires, and getting everything you can out of life. This is a very romantic approach to life, but hopefully you are also grounded enough to get by. Elmo's whole life is based on fantasy and his imagination. In the beginning he was a regular character, but now he spends most of his time in this fantasy world.

You are both somewhat extroverts. Like Elmo, you probably like to have some time to yourself, but you do appreciate spending time with your friends, and you aren't scared of social situations. Elmo spends some of his time with real friends, but he also needs some time just to chat it up with his goldfish.

i miss sleeping like a normal person...this is really starting to get old.

so i am sitting here in the library, procrastinating from doing work, shocker.  but i am having a difficult time trying to piece together how i am going to write this ramsey/yoder paper.  like in my head, i think i have a good argument, but trying to find the actual evidence to back it up using the two sources that we are supposed to use is tricky...like my argument is based more on several other yoder books, in addition to the one we are supposed to be using primarily.  so trying to actually find a way to structure my paper with good evidence is proving challenging at the moment, even though i know the argument is a solid one.  so the question we are supposed to be answering is, 'using ramsey, how does yoder get just war wrong?'  and what i want to argue is that for ramsey, yoder's account of just war comes across as wrong because of their differing christologies.  because of how they understand the work of christ, their views of the world and church are different, and therefore effect the way in which they understand the just war tradition.  i want to argue that yoder, who thinks in terms of a realized eschatology (because of his christology) cannot give the best account of just war because it does not fit in to his understanding of the witness of the church- but ramsey's understanding of just war as an account of statecraft works much more readily within his framework of the doctrine of two kingdoms, and that is how just war is meant to be understood.  this kind of ties back into what i wrote in my dissertation about how eschatology plays a large part in determining how one approaches the question of war.  so yeah...my thoughts are still sort of all over the place, i am having trouble articulating what i mean, and i can't find good passages out of my 2 main sources to back me up....grrr.  i am just getting annoyed now.

omg it is 3:30 am and i am still freaking awake....i have not gone to bed yet, and my alarm is going to go off in like 3 and a half hours....super.  this is just downright annoying.  why can i not sleep?  my eyelids are so heavy but for some reason my body just won't let me rest.  ::sigh::

so i am sitting here in the library and i really should be doing work, but i just can't find the motivation at the moment.  though i think i have figured out my schedule for next semester:
monday- no classes
tuesday- new testament (nt) 9-9:50; spiritual formation group 10-10:50; modern european christianity (mec) 11-12:15; the anglican tradition 4-6:30
wednesday- nt 9-9:50; old testament (ot) 11-12:15
thursday- nt 9-9:50; mec 11-12:15; mec precept 1:30-2:20
friday- ot precept 9-9:50; nt precept 10-10:50; ot 11-12:15

so this is quite similar to the schedule i have now, except my evening class on tuesday is a lot earlier and i have an added precept on thursday afternoon....but this means i will be able to keep pretty much the same work schedule, and tuesday won't be as long of a day as it is now where i am on campus from 8am til 9:30pm.

anyway.  so right now i am sitting here with the hopes of getting work done, but i doubt much will come of that.  i am waiting for michelle to get out of class at 5 and then we are going shopping because she needs some winter clothes (she is from florida and is a bit underprepared for nc, which i think is funny since nc doesn't really get that bad in the winter, haha).  though i am feeling pretty good about my work though for this week...it is just the work for the coming weeks that i am starting to get concerned about.  hauerwas just assigned us a paper due in a couple of weeks last night and i have absolutely no idea how i am going to answer the question he is asking us to write about...i really need to sit down and go through what we have read so far and think about that.  and then i need to start thinking about my exegesis paper for old testament...i mean, it isn't due til after thanksgiving, but i don't even know what passage i am exegeting yet.  and then the normal workload, plus 2 more papers for church history, a couple more papers for holy spirit, and whatever else i am forgetting off the top of my head, it is going to be busy...oh yeah, and studying for finals....that will be a big undertaking because we have gotten so much information this semester, especially in church history.  ok, i am done thinking about this stuff for now though.

i am glad it is almost the weekend (haha, i like how i consider wednesday afternoon almost the weekend) but this weekend should be fun.  friday night graham is coming with me to the hurricanes/flyers game...i am really looking forward to getting to see some hockey again!  i love it!  and then saturday sarah invited me out with a bunch of her friends to some sort of haunted corn maze...which doesn't thrill me all that much in and of itself, but i am looking forward to hanging out with people.  ok, well since i am, after all, sitting here in the library i should probably at least try to make some effort to do work....so i guess i am going to get to that at least for a little bit.

ugh, i have had a migraine most of the day and am getting ready to go back to bed...i slept most of the afternoon and didn't get any work done.  at least my stomach doesn't feel gross anymore...my head just still hurts a bit.  and today was supposed to be my productive day...oh well.  i guess i will just stay on campus tomorrow between work and my evening class because i will be more productive there than i would if i came back here for a couple of hours.  ok, well i really have nothing exciting to say at all and my head still hurts so i am going to go crawl back into my bed.

so timothy kimbrough, the rector of church of the holy family is finally back from sabbatical...this was his first service back.  i hadn't seen him since i went to holy family my senior year at elon.  but anyway, next sunday they are going to have a meeting for people who are considering joining the church.  then every sunday for the next 6 months there is a class that i would take before joining.  but at least i will be on my way to actually becoming a member of the episcopal church since technically i am still catholic.  but that is exciting.  

i just got back from duke gardens where i spent a couple of hours doing some reading and stuff.  it is sooo nice outside.  but then i came back because i need to start writing a paper...lucky me, ha.  i guess i should go do that...

i think my computer hates me...things keep going wrong with it, ugh.  and this computer is only a little over a year old...it shouldn't be having this many issues.  oh well.  anyway, i think i am going to head to bed soon since i didn't get much sleep last night.  tomorrow classes start back up and i am kind of glad about that...it will be nice to get back into a routine.  ok, well i really have nothing exciting to say...i just felt like venting about the stupidity of my computer.

ugh, i can't sleep...that is annoying.  especially because i am feeling pretty tired, i just kept tossing and turning and couldn't stop thinking about various things.  so now i am sitting on my couch watching nick at nite, ha.  so i suppose fall break is officially over for me...even though i don't have class til tuesday, i will be going in to work tomorrow so that is kind of getting back into the schedule of things.  i really enjoyed break a lot, but i think i am ready to get back into the swing of things, even though i know there is going to be a lot of work to do between now and thanksgiving.  but that's ok, i think i sort of thrive on the stress/pressure of school in a weird kind of way, as much as i complain about it sometimes, haha.  anyway.  i really have nothing exciting to say, at least nothing that i feel like writing about right now....perhaps i will try to go back to sleep....we'll so how successful that is.

so i decided to come home for a couple of days since i am on fall break right now, thank goodness.  so yesterday i came home, thought i am only staying til tomorrow night so i can in to work wednesday-friday.  when i got back yesterday i went to the beach with my aunt and the weather was perfect.  we went late afternoon so the sun wasn't glaring and it wasn't too hot and there was a nice breeze.  i definitely fell asleep.  anyway, i have pretty much just been a bum and am planning to continue with that while i am here.  i might try to get my hair cut tomorrow before i go back if there is an opening...it is about time to at least get a trim, though i might chop a few inches off again like last time.  it has been half a year since i have gotten it cut at all.  incidentally, the day i got it cut back in april was the day sam ended things with me, haha.  that is the only reason i know how long it has been since i have gotten it cut...that day is just sort of etched in my memory.  anyway, i have nothing exciting to report...nothing at all, so i am going to go back to watching the ellen degeneres show.  hopefully the weather will clear up a bit so i can go to the beach this afternoon.

OMG so i just cracked my flash drive which has ALLLLLL of my work from last year including my dissertation and ALLLLL of my work from this year so far, including the papers i have due tomorrow.  and now i have nothing.  NOTHING.  i can't get to any of my work.  my computer won't even read that i have my flash drive plugged in.  i am totally freaking out.  seriously.  OMG i am so stressed out right now.  not only because i have lost all of the work i have done in the past year and a half, but now i have to start over from scratch the work i have due tomorrow.  today is not a good day.  i want to cry.

haha, i am sitting in class right now...i caved in and brought my laptop in...wireless internet might be a dangerous thing for me.

coldplay was sooo good live...it was a great concert.  the seats were perfect, the weather was perfect, the whole night was really pretty perfect.  of course, we got stuck in concert traffic so we ended up missing the opening act, but neither of us cared so much.  so we got there just in time to grab some food and find our seats before coldplay came on.  oh it was great.  though by the time we finally got back to my apartment after 2 in the morning, we were both totally exhausted so we went to bed and didn't get up til almost noon.  rough life, i tell you.  i am still so tired though, so i think i might take a little nap...i will say more about the coldplay show later.

i'm going to coldplay tonight!  woohoo!  hopefully mike will be here in the next half hour and we don't hit any traffic on the way down...if we do that, then we might even still make it in time for the opening act...not that i care that much about that.  but yay, tonight will be fun!

today is a good day because:

1. i got a job in the rare books, manuscripts, and special collections library which should be really neat.

2. i love my war in the christian tradition class...we had the best discussion tonight in preceptorial.  seriously.

3. i got coldplay tickets tonight so mike and i are going to see them in charlotte on friday.  how excited am i?

4. i had one of those moments during the vigil we were having today to remember a murder victim in durham, bobby perry, where i realized how lucky i am, how much the world hurts, and how real the presense of god is.  all on one short moment.  so i don't know if that was necessarily a good thing as in, oh, it was happy...but good in the sense that it is those moments that helps shape me and guide me because most of my life is lived in between those moments of clarity.

woohoo i have a job!  so i will be working in the rare books, manuscripts, and special collections library all year...this should be interesting because duke has quite a good collection of things, including some greek bible manuscripts.   but anyway, my job will be dealing with new things coming in (well, not new things...but things new to the library), inventory, organizing, cataloguing, etc.  some of the work might be rather tedious, but at the same time it should still be interesting because of what the books and manuscripts are.  so i am excited.  and they need me to work enough hours so i will actually be able to get all of my work study allotment, which is good.  otherwise i would have had to find an additional job.  so yay for getting a job.  anyway, now i have to finish my work for class tonight....

yay, i am 23 today!  anyway, today actually wasn't all that exciting or out of the ordinary considering i had to be at orientation all day.  and it was rather boring.  i mean, i am excited about being at duke and think this is going to be a very good experience, but i am not too fond of sitting for hours on end listening to lots of people give me lots of information that isn't necessarily completely vital to me at this particular moment.  oh well.  yesterday we got to register for classes.  this semester i will be taking an old testament class (required), medeival church history (also required), the holy spirit and ministry, and war in the christian tradition.  i am particularly excited about this last class considering it was pretty much my dissertation topic.  and as sick as i was of actually writing my dissertation, the topic still totally fascinates me.  and that class is with hauerwas so i am excited about that too.  i made my first official friend today at duke as well...michelle.  she is very nice, just moved up here from tampa.  anyway, we hung out all evening...first she came back with me over to my apartment, then we ended up back at her town house eating pizza and watching a movie.  then her fiance got into town so i met him too.  they are getting married in december and he is moving up here then.  oh, so i bought my books today...or almost all of them...$324...ack.  fortunately, the bookstore here lets you open up a charge account, so you can charge your books with no interest, and as long as you pay it off before next semester, you are good.  so thank goodness for that!  otherwise i would have been screwed because i wouldn't have been able to afford more than a third of my books right now.  anyway, tomorrow is the last day of orientation, thank goodness.  and then tomorrow night mike is coming over again and we are watching fight club since i still have never seen it (i'm not sure how i haven't seen it yet...it seems like such a me movie) but yeah, overall i am feeling pretty good about life in general...a way i definitely haven't felt for a while.  i really have the feeling that duke is the right place for me.  among the people that are attending there are a wide range of beliefs and backgrounds religiously, and i think that is a very good thing because there will be more debate and discussion and it will help all of us to grow.  michelle and i were having this conversation earlier about how much more fun it is when you are surrounded by people that think differently from you (she and i being case in point) and that being in a place where everyone is the same doesn't challenge you or stretch you in ways that being among the people at duke might.  so i am excited.  and tired.  so i think i am going to go to bed now.  happy birthday to me 0:-)
I FINISHED IT!  IT IS IN THE MAIL!!
omg i am so tired and i hate my stupid dissertation....but i will stay up until it is done....i am soooo almost there...yet so far away.  le sigh

yeah, i am procrastinating again....but instead of doing it in my apartment, i am here in the library where at least there are fewer things to distract me.  but i do have 26 pages of my dissertation completely edited, so i guess that is progress....somehow it will all get done by tomorrow.  it would probably help if i stopped being a slacker.  but i can't help myself.  overall i have been fairly productive today so far though, so that is good.  so yeah.  i will finish this sometime in the next 24 hours, and mail this sucker off just in time to start my orientation at duke on wednesday.  but i must say, it surprises me that i am not really stressed out about my dissertation.  at all.  in fact it is rather disconcerting to me just how unstressed i am about it....but whatever...maybe it is just because mentally i have sort of moved on from st andrews and am looking ahead to duke...anyway, to change the subject, it is my birthday on thursday!  woohoo!  of course i have no plans for it, as usual.  oh well.  i think i am going to make myself some funfetti cupcakes.  and that will be the big excitement of my birthday, haha.  ok.  now that i have absolutely nothing interesting to say (not that any of this was interesting) i guess i will stop procrastinating and get back to work now.

ok....by this time on tuesday my dissertation will be in the mail.  but until then, i will be going crazy.  i keep finding parts of the paper where i need to add stuff in and i still need to write the conclusion.  i hope it all turns out alright.  it won't be the best thing i have ever written, but i think it will be ok.  as long as i get a mark decent enough to get the degree, that's all i care about at the moment.  which i am sure will happen.  but with the criticisms my supervisor was giving me on the work i have shown her so far, i can't help but worry.  and i know dr reed is overly-critical and i am trying to take some of her criticisms under consideration, but quite honestly i do not have the time or the motivation to deal with a lot of them.  it seems like everytime i send her a segment of what i have written, she ends up wanting me to take it in a different direction.  at this point i just say "screw it".  i am just going to do things my own way so this paper will have some semblence of coherence and also so it will actually be finished to turn in on time.  ugh i hate this stupid thing right now.  well, i guess i should get back to it.  ick.

omg i seriously have no motivation to finish my dissertation.  i mostly just sit here and stare dumbly at my computer screen.  it is almost done though...almost there.  ugh.

so last night i hung out with ken and people in burlington and went bowling, which was fun.  and i had cookout. mmmmm.  then today i had a dr's appointment and ran a couple of errands....i got a couple of candle sconces for the wall in my living room and put them up...they each hold 3 tea light candles and i have them lit now.  i think they look nice.  at the moment i am sitting here, doing minimal amounts of work on the dissertation while watching bring it on.  this movie never ceases to amuse me.  it always reminds me of elon though because i went to go see it my first week as a freshman with a group of people on my hall.

speaking of elon, but going off on completely different subject i haven't gone off on for quite a while...sam.  so i still have had absolutely no contact with him since that day a couple of months ago when i told him i couldn't have him as any part of my life anymore and haven't even thought about him all that much, or at least if i have it has been as a passing thought.  but it is like now that i am back in the area he has been on my mind a bit more.  not in the sense that i miss him or still want him or anything...(well, i mean, i still have those moments, but they pass) but more in the sense that i am terrified of running into him somewhere.  like i am totally worried that i will run into him at homecoming or something and don't think i would react in a very good way.  like if i saw him to talk to him i would probably be able to give off the appearance of being fine, but just the thought of seeing him gives me this sinking feeling in my stomach...like i know i would be really upset and would probably lose the battle in fighting off a major urge to cry.  but all this thinking is making me wonder if i am less over sam than i thought.  i mean, i am over him to the point where i don't particularly want to date him again but perhaps not to the point where i would be alright seeing him or where i think i could have serious feelings about someone else.  which kind of annoys me.  i guess it is almost like i am still wondering whether or not i will ever be able to have feelings for someone in the future like the ones i had for sam. but anyway.  i am just really freaked out by the possibility of running into him, slim though it is.  at least i knew when i was in scotland that there was absolutely no chance of that happening.  now that i am back in the area, there is actually a possibility, especially if i hang out with people in burlington.  but yeah...a part of me almost wants to not go to homecoming for fear of seeing him.  but that is a stupid reason not to go.  yes, the chances of running into him are much greater, but i will be around friends and it would be a shame to miss out of fun stuff just because i am worried about something that could happen.  ok, well enough on that.  i need to just stop thinking about it/him.  i am sure he probably doesn't think about me much, if at all and i would like it if that could be the same for me.

so my birthday is a week from today....23.  that is officially mid-twenties.  crazy.  if anyone wants to know, i am accepting gifts.  and personal checks ;-) or perhaps just a "happy birthday" will do.

alright, i guess that is enough procrastinating for now.

so much for going to bed....

ugh, i can't sleep... i woke up at like 1:45 and haven't been able to go back to sleep.  i thought perhaps if i watched boring infomercials on tv i would fall asleep, but that didn't work.  so then i thought, well, maybe if i take a nice warm bath.  but that didn't work either.  so now i have just given up and am out in the living room listening to bbc radio 4 via the internet.  that is one thing i definitely miss about the uk.  i mean, i like npr here, but bbc radio 4 is a million times better.  much better and varied programming.  now i am listening to the broadcast from earlier today of women's hour with jenny murray...ah, i listened to that every morning.  thank goodness i can still listen over the internet!  but seriously...npr should take a cue from the bbc.

so orientation for duke starts a week from tomorrow, yay!  i am excited to get started with things.  today owen and joyce got back from the mountains (they are my landlords) and the had me over for dinner along with jesus (as in hey-zeus) and carla (jesus is a spanish philosopher who is over here for a bit...owen, who is the chair of the philosophy department at duke is his mentor) and we had barbeque....mmmm.  but yeah, i think living here is going to be good.  owen and joyce are quite cool...i haven't met their daughter kate yet, but she is a senior at chapel hill, and i met ben on friday when i was moving in...he is 24 and in a band....he seems like a cool person, someone i would see myself being friends with.  but he headed back to california on saturday or something.  oh, but get this.  so owen is very into eastern philosophy and he is friends with the dalai lama.  i think that is pretty cool.

ok, well i guess maybe i should actually try to go to sleep again since i have to get up at a reasonable time to do more work on my dissertation tomorrow....of course, i could probably use this opportunity of being awake to work on it, and in fact that would probably do a good job of putting me to sleep, but i just can't be arsed to do it right now.
yay, the internet in my apartment works!  that is all.

well, i moved to durham on friday and have been pretty busy since then.  but the apartment is great and my parents were very helpful in getting me moved in.  so now, instead of being cluttered with lots of boxes and stuff, the apartment has some semblance of organization. though i still have a pile of clothes on my floor that i have yet to hang up/put in drawers.  oh well.  but anyway, friday and saturday were full of getting the apartment set up.  my parents left saturday afternoon, and then saturday night i drove to burlington to meet kacey and tammy for dinner.  at longhorn....mmmmmm. so i got back last night from a week of camp in md....god it was great.  i love camp.  i am never anything other than happy when i am there, even when things stress me out.  granted, i am almost always tired when i am there, but i would take tired and happy over sad and awake any day.  anyway.  friday the 29th i drove up to bethesda to spend the night at eliza's.  i stopped off at my new apartment along the way to pick up my key and take inventory of the furniture and stuff they already had in there.  i got to eliza's around 8 or so and we ate some pizza and i went to bed fairly early since i was tired from being on the road for like 10 hours.  then saturday afternoon i headed over to camp for a couple of hours to look at the curriculum and to decide if i liked it or not and if i wanted to deviate from it.  i was originally going to spend that night at camp even though the week wouldn't start til sunday, but i ended up going back to eliza's house for dinner and spent the night there again.  sunday morning i went back over to camp to meet matt and shannon to go over stuff for the week.  i am really glad we ended up getting shannon this week.  for a while matt and i were quite worried that we were going to be the only two couselors in the cabin with our 24 kids....but shannon, who used to date andy's son (andy is my old boss/camp manager) had emailed andy saying she was thinking about going into teaching and wanted some sort of immersion experience with kids, so she ended up coming up to help us.  thank goodness.  and she was about our age and very nice.  but anyway, i have decided that i don't really feel like writing in my lj right now since i am getting really tired (still recovering from a crazy week of camp and then driving all day yesterday) but i have much to say about camp....many stories.  so i will write about them tomorrow when i am more in the mood.

so sharon had this up and i found it highly amusing....

Revocation of the Independance of America

To the citizens of the United States of America, in the light of your failure to elect a competent President of the USA and thus to govern yourselves, we hereby give notice of the revocation of your independence, effective today.

Her Sovereign Majesty Queen Elizabeth II will resume monarchical
duties over all states, commonwealths and other territories. Except
Utah, which she does not fancy.

Your new Prime Minister (The Right Honourable Tony Blair, MP for the 97.85% of you who have until now been unaware that there is a world outside your borders) will appoint a Minister for America without the need for further elections.

Congress and the Senate will be disbanded. A questionnaire will be circulated next year to determine whether any of you noticed. To aid in the transition to a British Crown Dependency, the following rules are introduced with immediate effect:

1. You should look up "revocation" in the Oxford English Dictionary. Then look up "aluminium." Check the pronunciation guide. You will be amazed at just how wrongly you have been pronouncing it. The letter 'U' will be reinstated in words such as 'favour' and 'neighbour'; skipping the letter 'U' is nothing more than laziness on your part. Likewise, you will learn to spell 'doughnut' without skipping half the letters. You will end your love affair with the letter 'Z' (pronounced 'zed' not 'zee') and the suffix "ize" will be replaced by the suffix "ise." You will learn that the suffix 'burgh' is pronounced 'burra' e.g. Edinburgh. You are welcome to re-spell Pittsburgh as 'Pittsberg' if you can't cope with correct pronunciation.

Generally, you should raise your vocabulary to acceptable levels. Look up "vocabulary." Using the same thirty seven words interspersed with filler noises such as "uhh", "like", and "you know" is an unacceptable and inefficient form of communication. Look up "interspersed." There will be no more 'bleeps' in the Jerry Springer show. If you're not old enough to cope with bad language then you shouldn't have chat shows. Then you learn to develop your vocabulary, and then you won't have to use bad language as often.

2. There is no such thing as "US English." We will let Microsoft know on your behalf. The Microsoft spell-checker will be adjusted to take account of the reinstated letter 'u' and the elimination of "-ize."

3. You should learn to distinguish the English and Australian accents. It really isn't that hard. English accents are not limited to cockney, upper-class twit or Mancunian (Daphne in Frasier). You will also have to learn how to understand regional accents --- Scottish dramas such as "Taggart" will no longer be broadcast with subtitles. While we're talking about regions, you must learn that there is no such place as Devonshire in England. The name of the county is "Devon." If you persist in calling it Devonshire, all American States will become "shires" e.g. Texasshire, Floridashire, Louisianashire.

4. Hollywood will be required occasionally to cast English actors as the good guys. Hollywood will be required to cast English actors to play English characters. British sit-coms such as "Men Behaving Badly" or "Red Dwarf" will not be re-cast and watered down for a wishy-washy American audience who can't cope with the humour of occasional political incorrectness.

5. You should relearn your original national anthem, "God Save The Queen", but only after fully carrying out task 1. We would not want you to get confused and give up half way through.

6. You should stop playing American "football." There is only one kind of football. What you refer to as American "football" is not a very good game. The 2.15% of you who are aware that there is a world outside your borders may have noticed that no one else plays "American" football. You will no longer be allowed to play it, and should instead play proper football. Initially, it would be best if you played with the girls. It is a difficult game. Those of you brave enough will, in time, be allowed to play rugby which is similar to American "football", but does not involve stopping for a rest every twenty seconds or wearing full Kevlar body armour like nancies. We are hoping to get together at least a US Rugby sevens side by 2010.


You should stop playing baseball. It is not reasonable to host an event called the 'World Series' for a game which is not played outside of America. Since only 2.15% of you are aware that there is a world beyond your borders, your error is understandable. Instead of baseball, you will be allowed to play a girls' game called "rounders," which is baseball without fancy team strip, oversized gloves, collector cards or hotdogs.

7. You will no longer be allowed to own or carry guns. You will no longer be allowed to own or carry anything more dangerous in public than a vegetable peeler. Because we don't believe you are sensible enough to handle potentially dangerous items, you will require a permit if you wish to carry a vegetable peeler in public.

8. July 4th is no longer a public holiday. November 2nd will be a new national holiday, but only in England. It will be called "Indecisive Day."

9. All American cars are hereby banned. They are crap, and it is for your own good. When we show you German cars, you will understand what we mean. All road intersections will be replaced with roundabouts. You will start driving on the left with immediate effect. At the same time, you will go metric with immediate effect and without the benefit of conversion tables. Roundabouts and metrication will help you understand the British sense of humour.

10. You will learn to make real chips. Those things you call 'French fries' are not real chips. Fries aren't even French, they are Belgian. Though 97.85% of you (including the guy who discovered fries while in Europe) are not aware of a country called Belgium. Those things you insist on calling potato chips are properly called "crisps." Real chips are thick cut and fried in animal fat. The traditional accompaniment to chips is beer which should be served warm and flat. Waitresses will be trained to be more aggressive with customers.

11. As a sign of penance 5 grams of sea salt per cup will be added to all tea made within the Commonwealth of Massachusetts, this quantity to be doubled for tea made within the city of Boston itself.

12. The cold tasteless stuff you insist on calling "beer" is not actually beer at all, it is lager. From November 1st only proper British Bitter will be referred to as "beer," and European brews of known and accepted provenance will be referred to as "Lager." The substances formerly known as "American Beer" will henceforth be referred to as "Near-Frozen Gnat's Urine," with the exception of the product of the American Budweiser company whose product will be referred to as "Weak Near-Frozen Gnat's Urine." This will allow true Budweiser (as manufactured for the last 1000 years in the Czech Republic) to be sold without risk of confusion.

13. From November 10th the UK will harmonise petrol (or "gasoline," as you will be permitted to keep calling it until April 1st 2006) prices with the former USA. The UK will harmonise its prices to those of the former USA and the Former USA will, in return, adopt UK petrol price (roughly $6/US gallon -- get used to it).

14. You will learn to resolve personal issues without using guns, lawyers or therapists. The fact that you need so many lawyers and therapists shows that you're not adult enough to be independent. Guns should only be handled by adults. If you're not adult enough to sort things out without suing someone or speaking to a therapist, then you're not grown up enough to handle a gun.

15. Please tell us who killed JFK. It's been driving us crazy.

16. Tax collectors from Her Majesty's Government will be with you shortly to ensure the acquisition of all revenues due (backdated to 1776).

Thank you for your co-operation.
